PRD.md (Product Requirements Document)

Product Requirements Document (PRD)

1. Product Goal
The goal of MiniWardrobe is to help users select their daily outfits effortlessly by generating random combinations from their wardrobe based on selected filters.

2. Problem Statement
Users often experience decision fatigue when choosing daily outfits. MiniWardrobe aims to solve this by automating the selection process, saving users time and reducing stress.

3. Target Audience
- Students
- Young professionals
- Fashion-conscious individuals

4. User Roles
- User: Can add, edit, and view their wardrobe items and generated outfits.


5. User Scenarios
1. User adds a new clothing item: As a user, I want to upload a new clothing item to my wardrobe, so I can use it in outfit generation.
2. User generates an outfit: As a user, I want to generate an outfit based on my wardrobe, so I can quickly decide what to wear.

6. Functional Requirements
- The system must allow users to add items to their wardrobe.
- The system must generate random outfits from the wardrobe.
- Users must have their own profile, or they won't be able to interact with the website.


7. Non-Functional Requirements
- Performance: The app should generate outfits within 3 seconds.
- Reliability: The app should not crash during use.
- Security: User data must be encrypted and secure.
- Usability: The UI should be intuitive and simple to use.
- Scalability: Currently, the MiniWardrobe website is being developed locally, has not been deployed on a cloud platform, is not set up for scalability, and is designed to handle a limited number of users without load testing.

8. MVP Scope
- MVP Features: User login, wardrobe item management, outfit generation.
- Out-of-Scope: Social sharing, advanced outfit customization.

9. Acceptance Criteria
- Feature 1: Outfit generation works within 3 seconds.
- Feature 2: Users can add and edit wardrobe items.

